					<p>President Obama on Wednesday signed a reauthorization of <a href="http://www.washingtontimes.com/topics/the-export-import-bank/">the Export-Import Bank</a> that would raise its lending authority 40 percent to $140 billion by 2014 and pressed <a href="http://www.washingtontimes.com/topics/congress/">Congress</a> to pass a list of other top <a href="http://www.washingtontimes.com/topics/white-house/">White House</a> priorities aimed at creating jobs and boosting the economy.</p>
<p>Enough Republicans came to the 78-year-old bank’s aid to move the bill to the president’s desk earlier this month after conservatives in<a href="http://www.washingtontimes.com/topics/congress/">Congress</a> assailed it for meddling in the free market.</p>
